Whether you’re a student, a teacher, or simply a curious person that wants to learn, MIT OpenCourseWare (OCW) offers a wealth of insight and inspiration. There's videos, and a whole lot more!

OCW is a free and open online publication of material from thousands of MIT courses, covering the entire MIT curriculum, ranging from the introductory to the most advanced graduate courses. At the OCW website, you'll find that each course has a syllabus, instructional material like notes and reading lists, and learning activities like assignments and solutions. Some courses also have videos, online textbooks, or faculty insights on teaching.

Knowledge is your reward. There's no signup or enrollment, and no start/end dates. it's self-paced learning at its best.

Get the full picture at https://ocw.mit.edu.

• Exam averages of 30s, 40s, and 50s.
• Students discouraged from the sciences or are weeded out for the wrong reasons.
• Students weeded out of science classes with grades that scar their GPAs.
These students could have all one day have become amazing doctors or scientists. I have been in the same situation and almost gave up as well. My dream is to help students discover their potential and show them how fun, simple, and fascinating Organic Chemistry can be!  
I need your help to do this though!
Help me make a difference and help students skip the frustrations by trying out my videos that include analogies, tricks, and stories that make Organic Chemistry easy! Then just simply tell your friends + classmates and leave a comment if you think if I'm on the right track ;). 

If you'd like to get a Free Tutoring session and help support my videos, check out:
-----------www.OrgoMadeEasy.org-------

snippet.description:
Whether you’re a student, a teacher, or simply a curious person that wants to learn, MIT OpenCourseWare (OCW) offers a wealth of insight and inspiration. There's videos, and a whole lot more!

OCW is a free and open online publication of material from thousands of MIT courses, covering the entire MIT curriculum, ranging from the introductory to the most advanced graduate courses. At the OCW website, you'll find that each course has a syllabus, instructional material like notes and reading lists, and learning activities like assignments and solutions. Some courses also have videos, online textbooks, or faculty insights on teaching.

Knowledge is your reward. There's no signup or enrollment, and no start/end dates. it's self-paced learning at its best.

Get the full picture at https://ocw.mit.edu.

Channel banner photo by Nietnagel on Flickr (https://flic.kr/p/8WXxfK).

Greeted with comparisons to young Michael Jackson and Usher, Chris Brown arrived in 2005 as a squeaky-clean pop-R&B artist with "Run It!," the first debut single by a male artist to top the Billboard Hot 100 in over a decade. Within a few years, Brown became one of the biggest active pop stars with Chris Brown (2005) and Exclusive (2007), multi-platinum albums that produced five more Top Ten singles, including "Kiss Kiss" and "Forever." As a featured artist or duettist, he added to the count with hits such as "No Air," a ballad with Jordin Sparks. His streak of Top Ten albums was sustained with releases such as Graffiti (2009), the Grammy-winning F.A.M.E. (2011), and Fortune (2012). Brown's artistic scope has since continued to widen with Heartbreak on a Full Moon (2017) and Indigo (2019), albums as long as epic films.

I believe that a more informed audience raises the bar for storytelling. That examining the techniques used to tell great stories makes your own writing better and your appreciation for the stories deeper.

With Lessons from the Screenplay, I make videos that analyze movie scripts to examine exactly how and why they are so good at telling their stories. Part educational series and part love letter to awesome films, Lessons from the Screenplay aims to be a fun way to learn more about your favorite films and help us all become better storytellers.

I’ll be releasing new videos every couple weeks, and taking suggestions about what scripts I should look at in future episodes.
